B

  1. Create a function that given a positive integer \(n\) it creates n points at random in the square \([-1,1]\times [-1,1]\) then counts how many lie in the unit circle (radius=1) around the origin (0,0). The function should return 4*count/n and should also plot the random points, the square and the circle on the same plot. Color the inside points with a different color then outside points. Help yourself with the function from the last tutorial:

    incircle<-(function(x,y) sqrt(x^2+y^2)<=1)

  2. Take the ggplot from the first problem and decrease the size of the point closer to the origin and also color based on distance from the origin, like a sunflower.

Toggle output

 
isitpi<-function(n=100){
  x<-runif(n,-1,1)
  y<-runif(n,-1,1)
  incircle<-(function(x,y)sqrt(x^2+y^2)<=1)
  count<-sum(incircle(x,y))
  plot(sin(seq(-100,100,1)/100*pi),cos(seq(-100,100,1)/100*pi),type='l',col="green")
  lines(c(1,1,-1,-1,1),c(1,-1,-1,1,1),type='l',col="blue")
  points(x,y,col=ifelse(incircle(x,y),'red','black'))
  return(4*count/n)
}
isitpi(1000)

## [1] 3.132
montecarlo<-\(n){
  runif(n,-1,1)->x
  runif(n,-1,1)->y
  (seq(-1,1,0.05)*pi) %>% {data.frame(X=cos(.),Y=sin(.))}  %>% {ggplot(.)+geom_path(aes(x=X,y=Y,color="red")) + labs(x = "X-axis", y = "Y-axis", title = "Circle, Square and Points")+ geom_path(data=data.frame(X=c(1,-1,-1,1,1),Y=c(1,1,-1,-1,1)),aes(x=X,y=Y))+geom_point(data=data.frame(X=x,Y=y),aes(x=X,y=Y))} %>% print()
  (sqrt(x^2+y^2)<=1) %>% sum() %>% {.*4/n}
}
montecarlo(200)

## [1] 3.14
data.frame(X=x,Y=y) %>% ggplot()+
  geom_point(aes(x,y,colour=sqrt(x^2+y^2), size = sqrt(x^2+y^2)))+scale_size_continuous(range = c(0.5,2))+scale_color_gradient(low = "#58935A", high = "#F3C145")

isitpi<-function(n=100){
  x<-runif(n,-1,1)
  y<-runif(n,-1,1)
  incircle<-(function(x,y)sqrt(x^2+y^2)<=1)
  count<-sum(incircle(x,y))
  plot(sin(seq(-100,100,1)/100*pi),cos(seq(-100,100,1)/100*pi),type='l',col="green")
  lines(c(1,1,-1,-1,1),c(1,-1,-1,1,1),type='l',col="blue")
  points(x,y,col=ifelse(incircle(x,y),'red','black'))
  return(4*count/n)
}

Exploratory data analysis

In statistics, exploratory data analysis is an approach to analyzing data sets to summarize their main characteristics, often using statistical graphics and other data visualization methods

GGplot

The typical scatterplots, histograms, line charts, pie charts will work as long as you are presenting aggregation of the data in a compact form, for example:

mtcars %>% mutate(Brand=str_extract(rownames(.),"[^ ]*")) %>% group_by(Brand) %>% summarise(MPG=mean(mpg),HP=mean(hp)) %>% {print(.);.} %>% pivot_longer(2:3) %>% ggplot()+aes(y=Brand,weight=value)+geom_bar() +facet_wrap(vars(name),scales = "free_x")

Linear regression

In statistics, linear regression is a linear approach to modelling the relationship between a scalar response and one or more explanatory variables (also known as dependent and independent variables)

coeff<-lm(iris$Petal.Width~iris$Petal.Length)
ggplot(iris,aes(Petal.Length,Petal.Width,color=(Petal.Length*coeff[[1]][2]+coeff[[1]][1]>Petal.Width)))+geom_point()+geom_abline(intercept=coeff[[1]][1],slope=coeff[[1]][2])+
  labs(color = "Below the regression line?",title="Is there a correlation between petal length and width?")

A horizontal line would imply y does not depend on x, hence no correlation, a steep line would imply a strong correlation.

Dendrogram

A dendrogram is a diagram representing a tree. In hierarchical clustering, it illustrates the arrangement of the clusters produced by the corresponding analyses.

library(ggdendro)
hc <- hclust(dist(USArrests))
ggdendrogram(hc, rotate=T)

hc2<- hclust(dist(t(USArrests)))
ggdendrogram(hc2, rotate =F)

The shorter the path between two variables, the more similar they are.

Heat map

A heat map (or heatmap) is a data visualization technique that shows magnitude of a phenomenon as color in two dimensions.

heatmap(scale(mtcars), scale = "none")

A similar looking line above, would imply the 2 row variables are similar.

library("pheatmap")
sampleDists<-dist(mtcars)
sampleDistMatrix <- as.matrix(sampleDists)
pheatmap(sampleDistMatrix,
         clustering_distance_rows=sampleDists,
         clustering_distance_cols=sampleDists,
         )

Here we have the same variables as both columns and rows. The darker the square marking the intersection of a column and row variable, the more similar they are.
